ibility, technical/cognitive competence, calmness/judgment under pressure, decision-making, teamwork/communication, professional development/long-term suitability.\n\nWe need to weigh strengths and weaknesses, not focusing on single factor.\n\nLet's assess:\n\nA: Strengths: anticipates danger (reliability), sees complex connections (cognitive), excellent spatial vision (technical), very good leadership (teamwork). Weaknesses: show-off (could affect crew morale), not open to new ideas (resistance to learning, professional development). No explicit info on stress handling, calmness, decision speed. Overall: strong technical and situational awareness, but potential interpersonal issues and rigidity.\n\nB: Strengths: very conscientious (reliability), handles stress well (calm under pressure), good at assessing weather (technical), excellent computer skills (technical). Weaknesses: weak memory for numbers (could affect calculations), makes nasty remarks (teamwork/crew cooperation). Not open to new ideas? Not mentioned. Professional development unknown.\n\nC: Strengths: makes correct decisions quickly (decision-making), keeps calm in crisis (calmness), understands complicated technology (technical), quick decisions. Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork), egocentric (crew morale), not willing to further education (professional development). So technical and judgment good, but interpersonal issues.\n\nD: Strengths: responds to unexpected events adequately (adaptability), concentrates well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously (reliability). Weaknesses: hot temper (crew cooperation), regarded as know-it-all (could affect teamwork), maybe arrogance? Not open to new ideas? Not mentioned. Professional development unknown.\n\nNow we need to decide best overall. Long-distance flights require high reliability, technical competence, calm under prolonged stress, good decision-making, and especially teamwork/crew cooperation for long hours. Also professional development for ongoing training.\n\nCandidate B seems balanced: conscientious, handles stress, good weather assessment, computer skills, but interpersonal issue (nasty remarks) could be serious for crew. However, maybe can be mitigated? But we must not mitigate; we weigh as evidence.\n\nCandidate A has strong technical and leadership but show-off and not open to new ideas could affect crew and learning.\n\nCandidate C has good decision and calmness, but communication difficulty and egocentric, not willing to further education.\n\nCandidate D has problem solving and responsibility, but hot temper and know-it-all could be severe for crew.\n\nWhich is best? Possibly B, as stress handling and conscientiousness are crucial, and technical skills are solid. Interpersonal issue is nasty remarks, but maybe less severe than hot temper? Show-off and not open to ideas also problematic. Egocentric and communication difficulty also problematic.\n\nThus I might lean toward Candidate B as best, but note uncertainties: we lack info on B's teamwork beyond nasty remarks; we lack info on A's calmness; D's hot temper could be severe; C's communication issues may be big.\n\nI will vote Candidate B, with moderate confidence.\n\nNow produce public message summarizing evaluation and vote."}
